sec.p:
These guidelines are intended for use in quality-improvement programs that assess the standard of care expected of all physicians who perform TEVAR procedures. The issues addressed in this article include:
disease/lesion definition, diagnosis, and symptoms;
pretreatment evaluation;
patient selection;
procedure and technical aspects;
follow-up;
outcomes: technical success, clinical results, and complications based on the currently available data.

The larger the diameter of a thoracic aortic aneurysm, the higher the annual rupture risk [8, 9]:
>4 cm, 0.3%;
>5 cm, 1.7%;
>6 cm, 3.6%.

CTA evaluations can provide the following:
diameter and morphology of the aorta;
diameter and length of the proximal and distal necks;
intimal flap anatomy, extent of the dissection, and true and false lumen morphologies;
site of the primary entry tear;
re-entry site(s);
presence of thrombus or calcifications;
patency of the abdominal branches;
size, tortuosity, and disease status of iliac and femoral arteries.
